WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:05.870 --> 00:00:07.860
CHLOE COMBI: Thank you
very much for having me.

00:00:07.860 --> 00:00:09.560
Yes, my name is
Chloe Combi, and I'm

00:00:09.560 --> 00:00:11.690
here today to talk
to you about my book,

00:00:11.690 --> 00:00:14.180
"Generation Z, Their
Voices, Their Lives."

00:00:14.180 --> 00:00:17.020
And to reiterate, it
was a strange kind

00:00:17.020 --> 00:00:20.080
of genesis, this book, because
I'm not originally a writer.

00:00:20.080 --> 00:00:23.170
I was a school teacher.

00:00:23.170 --> 00:00:26.170
And I was a schoolteacher
straight out of university,

00:00:26.170 --> 00:00:29.160
and I taught in
quite challenging

00:00:29.160 --> 00:00:32.049
inner London schools.

00:00:32.049 --> 00:00:35.530
And there, I started my
own education charity

00:00:35.530 --> 00:00:38.550
called Write Club, which got
quite a lot of media attention.

00:00:38.550 --> 00:00:42.530
And because of that, i started
writing for newspapers,

00:00:42.530 --> 00:00:46.170
sort of darkly humorous pieces
about the realities of teaching

00:00:46.170 --> 00:00:46.750
life.

00:00:46.750 --> 00:00:49.855
And then from there, I
started writing features

00:00:49.855 --> 00:00:53.300
about, I guess, the grittier
aspects of teen life,

00:00:53.300 --> 00:00:56.750
so on grooming, and
busing, and gangland

00:00:56.750 --> 00:00:58.740
culture, and dog fighting.

00:00:58.740 --> 00:01:00.740
And yes, those did get
quite a lot of attention.

00:01:00.740 --> 00:01:03.510
I think they were
well timed as well.

00:01:03.510 --> 00:01:05.586
And what became very
clear was that there

00:01:05.586 --> 00:01:11.410
was this real need for this
window into teenage life.

00:01:11.410 --> 00:01:14.020
So Generation Z was born.

00:01:14.020 --> 00:01:17.936
And the concept, I
suppose, was simple enough.

00:01:17.936 --> 00:01:20.310
it was gonna take about 3
years to research and write it,

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:22.370
and I'd already kind of started.

00:01:22.370 --> 00:01:28.020
And the aim was to interview
2,000 teenagers, which I hit.

00:01:28.020 --> 00:01:31.220
So it's a big
sample of teenagers.

00:01:31.220 --> 00:01:34.250
And this isn't a book just
about gritty teenagers.

00:01:34.250 --> 00:01:37.460
It's from the most kind of
normal teenage experience

00:01:37.460 --> 00:01:41.320
to the most extreme, because
you have to get the whole range.

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:44.200
And so I think
it's a good insight

00:01:44.200 --> 00:01:48.470
into who teenagers in the
UK in the 21st century are.

00:01:48.470 --> 00:01:50.340
So who are Generation Z?

00:01:50.340 --> 00:01:52.550
Well, we're already
talked a bit about this.

00:01:52.550 --> 00:01:55.440
And actually,
originally, and I wanted

00:01:55.440 --> 00:01:58.010
to call this book
Generation I. I

00:01:58.010 --> 00:02:00.000
didn't want to call
it Generation Z,

00:02:00.000 --> 00:02:02.130
but we'll go back
into that later.

00:02:02.130 --> 00:02:03.930
And the small i,
because I thought

00:02:03.930 --> 00:02:07.530
the I for the
narcissistic I, which

00:02:07.530 --> 00:02:09.520
is a quality that this
generation are accused

00:02:09.520 --> 00:02:12.630
of a lot, the i,
which obviously is

00:02:12.630 --> 00:02:15.930
a sort of sly nod to Apple,
which most teenagers are

00:02:15.930 --> 00:02:18.385
completely enthralled
with, I'm sure you know.

00:02:18.385 --> 00:02:21.710
And obviously, i
for information,

00:02:21.710 --> 00:02:24.350
which is a real quality
of everyday life

00:02:24.350 --> 00:02:26.860
that we're all into.

00:02:26.860 --> 00:02:30.169
But there was a fear
that people would

00:02:30.169 --> 00:02:31.960
assume that it was a
book about technology,

00:02:31.960 --> 00:02:34.340
and it's not at all, because
I'm not a tech expert.

00:02:34.340 --> 00:02:36.790
So many things.

00:02:36.790 --> 00:02:38.480
So it became Generation Z.

00:02:38.480 --> 00:02:42.770
And actually Generation
Z was more of

00:02:42.770 --> 00:02:45.110
understood as a sociological
label than I realized.

00:02:45.110 --> 00:02:48.280
Because we've all
heard of Generation X.

00:02:48.280 --> 00:02:51.150
That was a real thing, and
there was books on Generation X.

00:02:51.150 --> 00:02:53.900
But Generation Y, which I'm
guessing most people in here

00:02:53.900 --> 00:02:57.160
fall into, kind of fell
through the cracks?

00:02:57.160 --> 00:02:59.535
And they were sometimes called
the millennial generation,

00:02:59.535 --> 00:03:03.640
and sometimes called the
post-baby boomer generation.

00:03:03.640 --> 00:03:05.500
So on a very simple
level, Generation Z

00:03:05.500 --> 00:03:10.750
are the children of
Generations Y and Generation X.

00:03:10.750 --> 00:03:12.170
And some of them
probably actually

00:03:12.170 --> 00:03:14.250
have grandparents now who
are Generation X, which

00:03:14.250 --> 00:03:15.083
is a bit terrifying.

00:03:18.190 --> 00:03:21.840
And for me, for my purposes,
they were teenagers.

00:03:21.840 --> 00:03:23.560
Everyone who I
interviewed in this book

00:03:23.560 --> 00:03:28.220
and who is in this book is
between the ages of 13 to 19.

00:03:28.220 --> 00:03:30.310
But for some people
writing about Generation Z,

00:03:30.310 --> 00:03:32.480
they widen that
cohort a little bit,

00:03:32.480 --> 00:03:35.640
and they're probably
more 12 to 22 year-olds.

00:03:35.640 --> 00:03:39.850
And currently there's a lot
of scare pieces about how

00:03:39.850 --> 00:03:42.820
the oldest of Generation Z are
about to enter the workplace,

00:03:42.820 --> 00:03:45.320
and ill-equipped they are, and
how they can't talk properly,

00:03:45.320 --> 00:03:47.611
and don't write properly,
and they write in text speak,

00:03:47.611 --> 00:03:49.130
and speak in text speak.

00:03:49.130 --> 00:03:53.380
But for my purposes,
they were teenagers.

00:03:53.380 --> 00:03:58.520
On a much more complex
level, they were as complex

00:03:58.520 --> 00:04:00.040
as any big group of people.

00:04:00.040 --> 00:04:02.550
They're as complicated, and as
strange, and as multifaceted,

00:04:02.550 --> 00:04:05.010
and as normal, and as
likable, and a unlikable,

00:04:05.010 --> 00:04:09.290
and as difficult to define
as any other large group.

00:04:09.290 --> 00:04:14.320
But there were themes, and
they were coming up again,

00:04:14.320 --> 00:04:15.376
and again, and again.

00:04:15.376 --> 00:04:17.000
They became quite
predictable, and they

00:04:17.000 --> 00:04:19.959
formed the natural
chapters of the book.

00:04:19.959 --> 00:04:21.839
And not in any order,
and I can't never

00:04:21.839 --> 00:04:25.360
remember all of these, but
they are sex, of course,

00:04:25.360 --> 00:04:31.620
and body, of course,
school, family, friendships

00:04:31.620 --> 00:04:37.730
and relationships, crime,
gender, class, race,

00:04:37.730 --> 00:04:39.290
the future, and technology.

00:04:44.790 --> 00:04:47.840
And technology particularly
I wanted to focus on a bit,

00:04:47.840 --> 00:04:49.420
obviously, considering
this audience.

00:04:49.420 --> 00:04:52.412
But also because
it is interesting

00:04:52.412 --> 00:04:54.870
for this generation, because
this is the first generation--

00:04:54.870 --> 00:04:57.120
this is the thing that
differentiates this generation.

00:04:57.120 --> 00:05:00.050
This is the first generation
that have grown up

00:05:00.050 --> 00:05:01.172
with the internet.

00:05:01.172 --> 00:05:02.630
They've grown up
with social media.

00:05:02.630 --> 00:05:03.710
They've grown up
with mobile phones,

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:06.100
and they've never known a
world without those things.

00:05:06.100 --> 00:05:08.225
The rest of it's probably
can remember a world when

00:05:08.225 --> 00:05:11.047
we didn't have those things,
but this generation has never

00:05:11.047 --> 00:05:12.880
known world without
them, and it's massively

00:05:12.880 --> 00:05:16.200
influenced who they are,
and how they've evolved,

00:05:16.200 --> 00:05:17.290
and how they think.

00:05:17.290 --> 00:05:21.132
And on the way, I
actually met a few kids,

00:05:21.132 --> 00:05:22.590
several who spring
to mind, and I'm

00:05:22.590 --> 00:05:24.900
gonna read you a
very short piece, who

00:05:24.900 --> 00:05:29.220
didn't realize that the
internet used to not exist.

00:05:29.220 --> 00:05:31.352
And they actually thought
I was pulling their leg,

00:05:31.352 --> 00:05:33.685
and they had to go and google
this fact, which obviously

00:05:33.685 --> 00:05:35.820
in ironic in and of itself.

00:05:35.820 --> 00:05:39.940
And I'm going to read you a
very short piece from the book.

00:05:39.940 --> 00:05:42.360
Now this is a trigger warning.

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:43.216
There's swearing.

00:05:43.216 --> 00:05:44.840
And if you do end up
reading this book,

00:05:44.840 --> 00:05:46.381
there's lots of
swearing, and there's

00:05:46.381 --> 00:05:47.790
lots of quite grim stuff in it.

00:05:47.790 --> 00:05:49.998
There's lots of really funny
and happy stuff as well,

00:05:49.998 --> 00:05:51.184
but there is swearing.

00:05:51.184 --> 00:05:53.350
And I'm not going to give
you the whole description,

00:05:53.350 --> 00:05:54.974
but these are three
boys, and basically

00:05:54.974 --> 00:05:57.390
them describing their
relationship every day

00:05:57.390 --> 00:05:58.670
with technology.

00:05:58.670 --> 00:06:01.790
And these three boys
have never read a book,

00:06:01.790 --> 00:06:04.520
except "Holes" by Louis Sachar,
because they were made to,

00:06:04.520 --> 00:06:06.103
and "Romeo and
Juliette," because they

00:06:06.103 --> 00:06:08.390
were made to at school.

00:06:08.390 --> 00:06:10.370
And they figured
that they probably

00:06:10.370 --> 00:06:13.630
accrued individually,
probably about $250 a week

00:06:13.630 --> 00:06:16.152
online in some way,
like gaming and so on.

00:06:16.152 --> 00:06:17.610
And these are three
different boys.

00:06:17.610 --> 00:06:21.529
One's called Raj, one's called
Abdi, and one's called Jouad,

00:06:21.529 --> 00:06:23.320
Do you know what I
found out the other day?

00:06:23.320 --> 00:06:24.950
That the internet
used to not exist.

00:06:24.950 --> 00:06:28.119
I didn't know that, and my
mind was all like, the fuck.

00:06:28.119 --> 00:06:29.160
And this is the next one.

00:06:29.160 --> 00:06:30.494
You're such a fool.

00:06:30.494 --> 00:06:31.910
Of course it didn't
used to exist.

00:06:31.910 --> 00:06:33.460
Mobile phones used to not exist.

00:06:33.460 --> 00:06:34.810
That's jokes, man.

00:06:34.810 --> 00:06:36.540
Can you imagine
no mobile phones?

00:06:36.540 --> 00:06:38.321
How would you even
talk to people?

00:06:38.321 --> 00:06:39.570
With your mouth, you dickhead.

00:06:42.090 --> 00:06:42.890
But no, man.

00:06:42.890 --> 00:06:45.914
The world would be so shit
without all the stuff we have.

00:06:45.914 --> 00:06:47.497
The teachers are all
negative about it

00:06:47.497 --> 00:06:50.380
and say it's sucking our
brains up, but that's bullshit.

00:06:50.380 --> 00:06:53.190
I was gaming with this sick
guy in Columbia the other day.

00:06:53.190 --> 00:06:54.920
He told me the
shit about Colombia

00:06:54.920 --> 00:06:56.670
that I didn't know
from geography lessons.

00:06:56.670 --> 00:06:58.070
That's educational.

00:06:58.070 --> 00:07:01.190
And he told me he gangbanged
my mum and sisters as well.

00:07:01.190 --> 00:07:04.140
But that's just
gaming, isn't it?

00:07:04.140 --> 00:07:05.590
You cuss each other to the max.

00:07:05.590 --> 00:07:07.400
It's psychological
banter, isn't it?

00:07:07.400 --> 00:07:10.900
You want them to get all pissed
off with you so that they lose.

00:07:10.900 --> 00:07:12.095
And it goes on.

00:07:15.070 --> 00:07:19.400
So that leads on to my
next question, which

00:07:19.400 --> 00:07:23.140
is do teenage boys and girls
engage with and get treated

00:07:23.140 --> 00:07:25.500
by the internet differently?

00:07:25.500 --> 00:07:27.900
well, that piece obviously
referenced gaming quite a lot.

00:07:27.900 --> 00:07:31.350
And I'm not gonna go into gaming
today, because I don't game,

00:07:31.350 --> 00:07:34.000
and I don't really know
enough about the logistics

00:07:34.000 --> 00:07:37.230
and the politics of it to
really go into in detail.

00:07:37.230 --> 00:07:39.190
What I do know is that
it's a real red button

00:07:39.190 --> 00:07:40.774
topic at the
moment, particularly

00:07:40.774 --> 00:07:42.190
to do with gender,
because there's

00:07:42.190 --> 00:07:45.310
this whole thing about how it's
a traditionally male thing,

00:07:45.310 --> 00:07:47.110
and more and more
girls want to game.

00:07:47.110 --> 00:07:48.930
But thumbs up to teenage boys.

00:07:48.930 --> 00:07:50.954
I will say that I met
very few who seemed

00:07:50.954 --> 00:07:52.120
to have a problem with that.

00:07:52.120 --> 00:07:55.330
They were very inclusive
about the idea.

00:07:55.330 --> 00:07:56.920
And that seems to
be more of an issue

00:07:56.920 --> 00:07:59.140
that a few gray men seem
to have a problem with,

00:07:59.140 --> 00:08:00.973
and I'll let you make
of that what you will.

00:08:03.960 --> 00:08:06.710
Both genders are, as
I'm sure you know,

00:08:06.710 --> 00:08:09.560
hugely, hugely, hugely
in social media.

00:08:09.560 --> 00:08:11.910
But that relationship's
evolving and changing really,

00:08:11.910 --> 00:08:12.730
really quickly.

00:08:12.730 --> 00:08:16.360
And I guess what
you would describe

00:08:16.360 --> 00:08:19.740
as the granddaddy of social
media, which would be Facebook,

00:08:19.740 --> 00:08:21.960
is in its death
throes with teenagers.

00:08:21.960 --> 00:08:23.220
They're completely out.

00:08:23.220 --> 00:08:26.420
They leaving by the hundreds
of thousands every day.

00:08:26.420 --> 00:08:28.050
And for the reason,
and I quote, it's

00:08:28.050 --> 00:08:31.500
because there's too many
old people on there.

00:08:31.500 --> 00:08:33.890
Their parents and their
grandparents are now on there,

00:08:33.890 --> 00:08:36.500
and 16 year-olds don't want
to hang out with their parents

00:08:36.500 --> 00:08:38.541
and grandparents in real
life, and they certainly

00:08:38.541 --> 00:08:39.480
don't online.

00:08:39.480 --> 00:08:42.020
I don't think teenagers
ever really embraced

00:08:42.020 --> 00:08:42.880
Twitter that much.

00:08:42.880 --> 00:08:45.380
I think it's much more of
a middle class adult thing.

00:08:45.380 --> 00:08:48.430
I think that middle class
adults love to go on Twitter

00:08:48.430 --> 00:08:50.730
and either show off or
get offended by things.

00:08:50.730 --> 00:08:52.867
I think that kids like
Twitter for stalking people,

00:08:52.867 --> 00:08:54.450
but other than that,
they don't really

00:08:54.450 --> 00:08:56.751
talk about in any kind
of passionate way.

00:08:56.751 --> 00:08:58.500
The three things that
they're really into,

00:08:58.500 --> 00:09:00.480
the mainstream stuff, there's
lots of underground stuff,

00:09:00.480 --> 00:09:02.790
but the three big ones
they're into at the moment

00:09:02.790 --> 00:09:06.484
are Snapchat,
Instagram, and YouTube.

00:09:06.484 --> 00:09:08.150
Now YouTube I'm not
gonna talk about too

00:09:08.150 --> 00:09:11.100
much, because it almost
deserves a talk unto itself.

00:09:11.100 --> 00:09:15.190
Because the YouTubers are
the teen-appointed new rock

00:09:15.190 --> 00:09:16.590
stars and royalty.

00:09:16.590 --> 00:09:21.880
They are huge, and these are
completely teen-led trends.

00:09:21.880 --> 00:09:24.900
Like, beyond the ages of
19, probably PewDiePie

00:09:24.900 --> 00:09:27.530
means absolutely
nothing to you, but they

00:09:27.530 --> 00:09:30.680
are like these little gods
to millions and millions

00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:31.250
of teenagers.

00:09:31.250 --> 00:09:34.670
And what's interesting is this
is not industry or adult-led.

00:09:34.670 --> 00:09:36.380
This is entirely
teen-led, which goes

00:09:36.380 --> 00:09:39.040
to show that they have quite
a lot of autonomy and power

00:09:39.040 --> 00:09:41.420
on the internet.

00:09:41.420 --> 00:09:43.130
But the one I wanted
to talk about today

00:09:43.130 --> 00:09:45.620
was actually Instagram,
because there I

00:09:45.620 --> 00:09:50.070
think there is a really
interesting gender

00:09:50.070 --> 00:09:53.200
political paradigm
that comes up.

00:09:53.200 --> 00:09:55.740
Male vanity is a thing,
and it's a growing thing,

00:09:55.740 --> 00:09:58.800
and there's lots of issues
about boys and their body image.

00:09:58.800 --> 00:10:00.760
But if you look at
the Instagram page

00:10:00.760 --> 00:10:03.200
of the average teenage
boy, it revolves

00:10:03.200 --> 00:10:05.910
around stuff or action.

00:10:05.910 --> 00:10:08.100
Stuff being cool, if
they're a bit older,

00:10:08.100 --> 00:10:12.520
cool cars, cool headphones,
cool shades, school threads.

00:10:12.520 --> 00:10:15.380
And or it revolves
around action,

00:10:15.380 --> 00:10:17.906
so like, on holiday
surfing with their mates,

00:10:17.906 --> 00:10:19.780
or on the side of a
mountain with their hands

00:10:19.780 --> 00:10:20.974
in the air at sunset.

00:10:20.974 --> 00:10:22.390
Or if they're a
bit younger, maybe

00:10:22.390 --> 00:10:24.514
like looning around a
classroom with their friends,

00:10:24.514 --> 00:10:26.920
and making those kinds of signs.

00:10:26.920 --> 00:10:30.290
Girls Instagram page
revolve around the self.

00:10:30.290 --> 00:10:34.610
And by the self, I mean the
selfie self-- very stylized,

00:10:34.610 --> 00:10:37.250
very sexualized, the duck face.

00:10:37.250 --> 00:10:41.660
Now it's the fish face,
which duck face is very 2015

00:10:41.660 --> 00:10:44.660
and we're nearly 2016.

00:10:44.660 --> 00:10:48.860
Lots and lots of pouting,
and lots of focus on body,

00:10:48.860 --> 00:10:53.330
in a very kind of
sexualized way.

00:10:53.330 --> 00:10:55.820
And when I was writing the
book, the girls, lots of girls,

00:10:55.820 --> 00:10:57.980
told me about selfie parties.

00:10:57.980 --> 00:11:00.800
And selfie parties,
ostensibly, I guess,

00:11:00.800 --> 00:11:03.260
are like slumber parties.

00:11:03.260 --> 00:11:06.420
Butt the whole idea is
you get together, sit

00:11:06.420 --> 00:11:08.840
around each other's houses,
and rather than watch

00:11:08.840 --> 00:11:12.900
a movie or talk about boys,
you doll each other up,

00:11:12.900 --> 00:11:15.530
take hundreds or
thousands of selfies,

00:11:15.530 --> 00:11:18.370
manipulate them, face
tune them, although you

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:21.300
don't admit to that, and
then put them on Instagram.

00:11:21.300 --> 00:11:23.060
And there's a
competitive element

00:11:23.060 --> 00:11:27.900
as to who gets the most
likes or the most comments.

00:11:27.900 --> 00:11:31.820
And obviously, the holy grail of
those comments come from boys.

00:11:31.820 --> 00:11:37.020
And I think that that's
pushing both genders

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:40.940
into roles I think a lot of them
are really uncomfortable with.

00:11:40.940 --> 00:11:43.350
Girls become the
exhibitionists on trial,

00:11:43.350 --> 00:11:46.050
and boys become the
voyeurs and the judges.

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:49.270
And lots of them have said
to me, I don't like this.

00:11:49.270 --> 00:11:54.450
And what a shame in 2015,
where most adults, probably

00:11:54.450 --> 00:11:56.680
with the exception
of like Donald Trump,

00:11:56.680 --> 00:12:00.100
have decided that beauty
pageants are really naff,

00:12:00.100 --> 00:12:03.750
