technology to organize crime,

00:24:34.921 --> 00:24:36.920
and utilizing technology
to threaten each other,

00:24:36.920 --> 00:24:40.230
and using technology to recruit.

00:24:40.230 --> 00:24:42.640
And the answer to
that is, hell yes.

00:24:42.640 --> 00:24:43.650
Absolutely they are.

00:24:43.650 --> 00:24:45.960
They're using technology
very, very, very cleverly,

00:24:45.960 --> 00:24:48.510
and very smartly.

00:24:48.510 --> 00:24:52.050
And it's very, very
simple as to why.

00:24:52.050 --> 00:24:55.060
20 years ago, anyone on the
street affiliated to crime

00:24:55.060 --> 00:24:58.770
had to rely on what was
going on and to understand

00:24:58.770 --> 00:25:01.080
what was going on
through word of mouth,

00:25:01.080 --> 00:25:02.540
through face-to-face
confrontation,

00:25:02.540 --> 00:25:04.920
through graffiti, through
the colors that they wore.

00:25:04.920 --> 00:25:08.970
But now particularly with
mobile phones and social media,

00:25:08.970 --> 00:25:11.840
this internalized
endless newspaper

00:25:11.840 --> 00:25:14.570
as to street news, beefs.

00:25:14.570 --> 00:25:18.530
But also any organized crime
that you've heard of, probably

00:25:18.530 --> 00:25:22.330
in the last 8 to 10 years, so if
you think about the 2011 riots,

00:25:22.330 --> 00:25:24.240
if you heard about
that big thing

00:25:24.240 --> 00:25:26.950
that kicked off in Walthamstow
between two rival girl gangs

00:25:26.950 --> 00:25:31.220
last week, organized gang-rapes,
organized robberies, organized

00:25:31.220 --> 00:25:33.800
movements against the police,
or what they call the feds,

00:25:33.800 --> 00:25:38.830
they absolutely will have had
some element of technology

00:25:38.830 --> 00:25:42.990
driving it, and
probably quite a lot.

00:25:42.990 --> 00:25:45.500
So it's definitely not
just a middle class

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:47.620
concern, the internet.

00:25:47.620 --> 00:25:50.490
So on a slightly
more uplifting note,

00:25:50.490 --> 00:25:54.740
will technology save the
future for young people?

00:25:54.740 --> 00:25:57.430
Loads of scaremongery
articles, as I'm sure

00:25:57.430 --> 00:25:59.340
you know from adults
about how technology,

00:25:59.340 --> 00:26:00.840
in particular the
internet, is gonna

00:26:00.840 --> 00:26:03.480
signal the end of civilization.

00:26:03.480 --> 00:26:06.050
All newspapers will
become Buzzfeed.

00:26:06.050 --> 00:26:09.410
All television shows
will be fronted

00:26:09.410 --> 00:26:13.860
by AI versions of Davina
McCall and Stephen Fry.

00:26:13.860 --> 00:26:16.950
And all shops will
be manned by robots.

00:26:16.950 --> 00:26:21.095
Teenagers don't see
technology like that at all.

00:26:21.095 --> 00:26:23.220
They don't see it as the
destruction of the future.

00:26:23.220 --> 00:26:25.730
They see it as the
creation of their future.

00:26:25.730 --> 00:26:28.970
And they're very,
very, very innovative,

00:26:28.970 --> 00:26:31.570
and very creative
on the internet.

00:26:31.570 --> 00:26:34.150
They vie, and they vlog,
they blog, they YouTube,

00:26:34.150 --> 00:26:35.510
they create websites.

00:26:35.510 --> 00:26:39.770
I do a Sunday show
with a lad who's 17.

00:26:39.770 --> 00:26:44.810
He started an internet radio
show in his bedroom age 12.

00:26:44.810 --> 00:26:47.360
Now age 17, he's sometimes
pushing seven figures

00:26:47.360 --> 00:26:49.535
of listeners, and he's
courted by all these CEOs

00:26:49.535 --> 00:26:51.160
and brands of the world.

00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:53.870
And so that's just
a good example.

00:26:53.870 --> 00:26:56.830
But I think what the
problem is there's

00:26:56.830 --> 00:26:58.760
too much interface
with institutions

00:26:58.760 --> 00:27:04.030
that children, that teenagers,
are caught up in that are too

00:27:04.030 --> 00:27:06.370
wrapped up with the path.

00:27:06.370 --> 00:27:09.060
And the best I can think of,
to finish this off today,

00:27:09.060 --> 00:27:11.870
is education.

00:27:11.870 --> 00:27:18.340
And when I was teaching I lost
count of the number of times

00:27:18.340 --> 00:27:20.815
that I asked a kid to go
read something from the book,

00:27:20.815 --> 00:27:23.900
or read a book, and they would
whinge and complain or not

00:27:23.900 --> 00:27:24.820
do it.

00:27:24.820 --> 00:27:27.040
And then as soon as you
gave them a screen, and said

00:27:27.040 --> 00:27:28.706
go and read this on
a screen, whether it

00:27:28.706 --> 00:27:31.870
was a laptop, or a
computer, whatever,

00:27:31.870 --> 00:27:33.360
they go away and happily do it.

00:27:33.360 --> 00:27:34.735
And they wouldn't
complain, and it would be

00:27:34.735 --> 00:27:35.943
a completely different thing.

00:27:38.400 --> 00:27:40.824
Hard, hard fact is
we have a big reading

00:27:40.824 --> 00:27:42.740
problem in this country,
huge reading problem,

00:27:42.740 --> 00:27:45.430
and it's gonna affect the
future of our country.

00:27:45.430 --> 00:27:49.060
There's too many kids and
teenagers who are illiterate.

00:27:49.060 --> 00:27:51.760
there are far too many who are
below the level of literacy

00:27:51.760 --> 00:27:55.580
that they should be,
and I'd say probably 85%

00:27:55.580 --> 00:27:57.962
if not more kids don't
read enough, particularly

00:27:57.962 --> 00:28:00.170
when you compare them to
other countries and the kind

00:28:00.170 --> 00:28:03.220
of reading levels
that they're doing.

00:28:03.220 --> 00:28:06.445
And I think if we don't
do something about this,

00:28:06.445 --> 00:28:08.320
we are heading for a
problem, because there's

00:28:08.320 --> 00:28:09.830
no way to sugarcoat it.

00:28:09.830 --> 00:28:12.860
Reading is essential for
academic and intellectual

00:28:12.860 --> 00:28:17.620
development, both as an
individual and as a country.

00:28:17.620 --> 00:28:20.240
I think the remedy
might be technology.

00:28:20.240 --> 00:28:22.920
I think schools might be
too beholden to this idea

00:28:22.920 --> 00:28:25.530
that reading has to happen
in an armchair in a corner

00:28:25.530 --> 00:28:27.180
in a big tome of Dickens.

00:28:27.180 --> 00:28:30.930
And they have to embrace that
this is how kids want to read.

00:28:30.930 --> 00:28:33.710
I did a lot of work
for Wellington College

00:28:33.710 --> 00:28:37.730
under Sir Anthony Seldon, who's
a real educational progressive.

00:28:37.730 --> 00:28:43.530
Six years ago, he got rid of 75%
of the books in their library,

00:28:43.530 --> 00:28:46.890
and replaced them with
screens and instructive forms

00:28:46.890 --> 00:28:50.040
of reading, and they went
on to have unparalleled

00:28:50.040 --> 00:28:52.260
academic success year-on-year.

00:28:52.260 --> 00:28:55.860
Now, Wellington College is an
incredibly wealthy institution,

00:28:55.860 --> 00:28:58.430
and state schools
don't have that kind

00:28:58.430 --> 00:29:00.420
of equipment or money.

00:29:00.420 --> 00:29:03.650
I'm a huge fan of the state
system, but it is buckling.

00:29:03.650 --> 00:29:06.440
It is buckling under
a weight, and it's

00:29:06.440 --> 00:29:08.340
heading for serious problems.

00:29:08.340 --> 00:29:10.710
This is a government that
is tearing apart the state

00:29:10.710 --> 00:29:13.260
education system piece
by piece, and it's

00:29:13.260 --> 00:29:15.560
in desperate need of help.

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:19.130
Year-on-year, classroom
sizes increase.

00:29:19.130 --> 00:29:24.480
So you'll have in one
classroom sometimes 35 kids.

00:29:24.480 --> 00:29:28.050
And within that class
size, you can have kids

00:29:28.050 --> 00:29:32.170
with an ability range from
serious learning difficulties

00:29:32.170 --> 00:29:33.280
to genius.

00:29:33.280 --> 00:29:38.460
So not every child
in there is gonna

00:29:38.460 --> 00:29:40.290
have the learning
that they need.

00:29:40.290 --> 00:29:43.190
Some kids really work
well with one-on-one.

00:29:43.190 --> 00:29:46.450
Some kids work really
well in groups.

00:29:46.450 --> 00:29:48.160
Some kids love rote learning.

00:29:48.160 --> 00:29:50.520
Some kids love doing
project learning.

00:29:50.520 --> 00:29:53.530
So all the kids in the state
system I spoke to pretty much

00:29:53.530 --> 00:30:00.470
told me that the internet has
become their primary source

00:30:00.470 --> 00:30:04.550
of top-up learning, because they
simply cannot facilitate this,

00:30:04.550 --> 00:30:07.110
the kind of learning
that every child needs.

00:30:07.110 --> 00:30:10.110
And I think this
needs to be embraced.

00:30:10.110 --> 00:30:13.390
I think there needs to be a
collaboration between perhaps

00:30:13.390 --> 00:30:15.750
companies like this and
all the many like them,

00:30:15.750 --> 00:30:19.710
even though they're not
as good, in education,

00:30:19.710 --> 00:30:23.252
because I think the state
system is in dire need of help.

00:30:23.252 --> 00:30:25.150
So more online
learning resources.

00:30:25.150 --> 00:30:26.200
We're not reading enough.

00:30:26.200 --> 00:30:27.730
Kids don't have
access to books, so

00:30:27.730 --> 00:30:31.880
what about a heavily
promoted teen marketed

00:30:31.880 --> 00:30:34.010
online library service?

00:30:34.010 --> 00:30:38.416
